below shows the size of the shortest gap after each play.

\begin{tabular}{|c|c|c|}\hline after & 1989 & 1492 \\ \hline 1 & 994 & 745 \\ 2 & 496 & 372 \\ 3 & 247 & 185 \\ 4 & 123 & 92 \\ 5 & 61 & 45 \\ 6 & 30 & 22 \\ 7 & 14 & 10 \\ 8 & 6 & 4 \\ 9 & 2 & 1 \\ \hline\end{tabular}

Evidently $B$ can always play the first 10 tokens. But $A$ can fit both tokens 10 and 11 into his gap of 2, whereas $B$ can only fit token 10. So $B$ loses for more than 10 tokens, and wins for at most 10 tokens.

Let M be the midpoint of AC, N the midpoint of BD. Take P so that PM is parallel to BD and PN is parallel to AC. Now EM is a midline of ABC, so area AEM = $\frac{\text{area ABC}}{4}$. Similarly, area AHM = $\frac{\text{area ADC}}{4}$. So area MHAE = $\frac{\text{area ABCD}}{4}$. But MP is parallel to EH, so area MEH = area PEH. Hence

\[
\begin{align*} 
\text{area } \text{PHAE} &= \text{area } \text{PEH} + \text{area } \text{AEH} \\ 
&= \text{area } \text{MEH} + \text{area } \text{AEH} \\ 
&= \text{area } \text{MHAE} = \frac{\text{area } \text{ABCD}}{4} 
\end{align*}
\]

Similarly for area PEBF and the other quadrilaterals.
